1. What is the dot operator used for?
-->The dot operator is used to access members of a class or object.
👉 Members include:
Variables (fields)
Methods
Inner classes
📌 Example:
class Student {
    String name = "Karthikeya";

    void display() {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}
Student s = new Student();
s.display(); // accessing method using dot operator



2. Can the dot operator be used with static members?
-->✔ Yes
👉 Static members are accessed using:
ClassName.member


3. What is the difference between object.method() and ClassName.method()?
-->
| Feature          | `object.method()` | `ClassName.method()` |
| ---------------- | ----------------- | -------------------- |
| Used for         | Instance methods  | Static methods       |
| Requires object? | ✔ Yes             | ❌ No                 |
| Memory           | Object must exist | No object needed     |



4. What happens when you use a dot operator on a null reference?
-->❌ It throws:
    👉 NullPointerException
    📌 Example:
    Test t = null;
    t.instanceMethod(); // ❌ Runtime error
    👉 Reason:
    You are trying to access a method using an object that does not exist in memory
